        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Seems like `if !has('nvim')` should be used, like in regular vimrc.\r\n\r\nBut if a project wishes to include a `.vimrc` file that is meant to be used _specifically_ for Vim, the onus should not be on them to guard against Neovim also including that file.\r\n\r\nThe argument against this is the exact same as not using `~/.vimrc` as the main Nvim configuration file in the first place (as @clason mentioned).\r\n\r\nThank you for taking the time to put together an issue, but given there are perfectly viable alternatives I'm going to close this as a \"won't fix\".",
